<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 1 (03/01/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
Course info. Basic notions on autonomous ODEs. Local and global existence conditions.
Examples and counterexamples. Comparison functions. A basic stability result for
scalar nonlinear differential equations. Lyapunov criterion for
stability.
<br><br>
<a href="ncs_05_slides_lec1.pdf">Slides</a> Lecture 1</span>
<br><br>


<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 2 (03/03/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
Global asymptotic and local exponential stability. Radial unboundedness.
Converse theorems. Local and global ultimate boundedness.
Robustness of exponential stability to vanishing perturbations.
Robustness of asymptotic stability to nonvanishing perturbations.
Total stability theorem. Stability of cascade connected systems.<br><br>
<a href="ncs_05_slides_lec2.pdf">Slides</a> Lecture 2</span>
<br><br>

<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 3 (03/08/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
Input-to-state stability (ISS). BIBS and CICS property. GAS (GES)
does not imply ISS. ISS-Lyapunov function. Examples. ISS-pair.
Cascade of an ISS and a GAS system is GAS. Application to the robust control of
a rotating rigid body. <br><br>
<a href="ncs_05_slides_lec3.pdf">Slides</a> Lecture 3</span>
<br><br>

<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 4 (03/10/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
Changing ISS-pairs.
Cascade of ISS systems is ISS. Another equivalent characterization
of ISS systems. Interconnected ISS systems. Small-gain theorem.
<br><br>
<a href="ncs_05_slides_lec4.pdf">Slides</a> Lecture 4</span>
<br><br>

<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 5 (03/15/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
Dissipative systems, supply rate, storage function,
dissipation inequality. Dissipative static nonlinearities.
Dissipativity and stability. Zero-state detectability. Finite
L2-gain, passive and sector bounded systems. A Lyapunov
charaterization of dissipation inequality. Applications to
finite L2-gain and  passive systems. Hamilton-Jacobi inequality.
Feedback interconnected dissipative systems. Conditions for the
stability of the interconnected system. A small-gain theorem for the
stability of interconnected detectable finite L2-gain systems.
Stability of a passive detectable system interconnected with a
dissipative static nonlinearity.
<br><br>
<a href="ncs_05_slides_lec5.pdf">Slides</a> Lecture 5</span>
<br><br>

<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 6 (03/17/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
On feedback passivation. Relative degree one. Weakly minimum phase systems.
Dissipativity and frequency response. (Strictly) positive real transfer
functions. Positive real and Kalman-Yakubovich-Popov lemma. Positive realness
and passivity. Lur'e problem. Absolute stability.
<br><br>
<a href="ncs_05_slides_lec6.pdf">Slides</a> Lecture 6</span>
<br><br>

<span
 style="font-family: &quot;Comic Sans MS&quot;; color: blue;">
<h3>Lecture 7 (03/22/05)</h3></span>
<span style="font-size: 12pt">
Loop transformations. Circle criterion. Popov criterion. <br><br>
